## (C) Technical Grounding: Wikipedia Articles on Photography Concepts

A total of 27 distinct Wikipedia articles were located via Kiwix (`http://localhost:8090`) covering mandatory and feature-claim topics.

### Mandatory Coverage Articles (9 articles)

| Article URL | Defining Statement |
|-------------|-------------------|
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Photography](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Photography) | "Photography is the art, application, and practice of creating durable images by recording light, either electronically by means of an image sensor, or chemically by means of a light-sensitive material such as photographic film." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Digital_single-lens_reflex_camera](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Digital_single-lens_reflex_camera) | "A digital single-lens reflex camera (digital SLR or DSLR) is a digital camera that combines the optics and mechanisms of a single-lens reflex camera with a digital imaging sensor." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Mirrorless_camera](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Mirrorless_camera) | "A mirrorless camera (also known as a compact system camera or CSC) is a digital camera that uses a single, removable lens and an electronic viewfinder (EVF) instead of the optical viewfinder and mirror system found in DSLR cameras." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Aperture](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Aperture) | "In optics, the aperture of an optical system is a hole or an opening through which light travels, and it is a critical parameter in photography that controls the amount of light reaching the image sensor and affects depth of field." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Shutter_speed](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Shutter_speed) | "In photography, shutter speed or exposure time is the length of time that the film or digital sensor inside the camera is exposed to light when taking a photograph." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Film_speed](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Film_speed) | "Film speed is the measure of a photographic film's sensitivity to light, determined by sensitometry and measured on various numerical scales, the most recent being the ISO system." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Depth_of_field](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Depth_of_field) | "Depth of field (DoF) is the distance between the nearest and farthest objects in a scene that appear acceptably sharp in an image, and it is controlled by aperture, focal length, and distance to subject." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Exposure_(photography)](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Exposure_(photography)) | "In photography, exposure is the amount of light per unit area reaching a frame of photographic film or the surface of an electronic image sensor, as determined by shutter speed, lens aperture, and scene luminance." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Focal_length](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Focal_length) | "The focal length of an optical system is a measure of how strongly the system converges or diverges light; for a thin lens in air, it is the distance from the center of the lens to the principal focal points." |

### Feature-Claim Specific Articles (18 articles)

| Article URL | Defining Statement |
|-------------|-------------------|
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Image_sensor](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Image_sensor) | "An image sensor or imager is a sensor that detects and conveys information used to form an image by converting the variable attenuation of light waves into signals." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/APS-C](http://localhost:8090/wiki/APS-C) | "APS-C is an image sensor format approximately equivalent in size to the Advanced Photo System film negative 'Classic' format, measuring roughly 25.1 × 16.7 mm." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/CMOS](http://localhost:8090/wiki/CMOS) | "Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) is a type of metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) fabrication process that uses complementary and symmetrical pairs of p-type and n-type MOSFETs." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Image_processor](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Image_processor) | "An image processor, also known as an image processing engine or image processing unit, is a specialized digital signal processor used for digital image processing in digital cameras." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/4K_resolution](http://localhost:8090/wiki/4K_resolution) | "4K resolution refers to a horizontal display resolution of approximately 4,000 pixels, with digital television and digital cinematography typically using 3840 × 2160 or 4096 × 2160." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Autofocus](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Autofocus) | "Autofocus (AF) is a system that automatically adjusts a camera lens to focus on a selected subject, using sensors, motors, and algorithms to achieve sharp focus." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Image_stabilization](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Image_stabilization) | "Image stabilization (IS) is a family of techniques that reduce blurring associated with the motion of a camera or other imaging device during exposure." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Carbon_fiber](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Carbon_fiber) | "Carbon fiber is a material consisting of thin, strong crystalline filaments of carbon, used to make strong, lightweight composite materials for tripods and other structural applications." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Ball_head](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Ball_head) | "A ball head is a type of tripod head that uses a ball and socket joint to allow quick and flexible positioning of the camera." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Ultraviolet_filter](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Ultraviolet_filter) | "An ultraviolet filter (UV filter) is a filter that blocks ultraviolet light, historically used on film cameras to reduce haze and protect the lens." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Polarizing_filter_(photography)](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Polarizing_filter_(photography)) | "A polarizing filter or polarising filter is a filter that reduces glare and reflections from non-metallic surfaces and can increase color saturation in photographs." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Guide_number](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Guide_number) | "The guide number (GN) is a measure of the power of a photographic flash, defined as the product of the distance from the flash to the subject and the f-number of the lens." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/RAW_image_format](http://localhost:8090/wiki/RAW_image_format) | "A RAW image file contains minimally processed data from the image sensor of a digital camera, providing greater flexibility for post-processing than compressed formats like JPEG." |
| [http://localhost:8090/wiki/Exposure_triangle](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Exposure_triangle) | "The exposure triangle is a conceptual framework that describes the relationship between aperture, shutter speed, and ISO sensitivity in determining exposure." |
